This paper deals with the problem of triangulating a planar point set, which is a fundamental problem in computational geometry. Therefore, cs.CG (Computational Geometry) is the most likely sub-category. The paper also involves dynamic programming and graph theory, which are common in cs.DS (Data Structures and Algorithms) and cs.CC (Computational Complexity) respectively. The use of heuristics and computer assistance suggests cs.DM (Discrete Mathematics) as another possible sub-category. Finally, the paper involves proving the NP-hardness of a problem, which is a common theme in cs.GT (Computer Science and Game Theory).
